const Q_CRK_2014=[{"id": "objective>CRK>2014>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The name of the subject you are doing is ?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mathematics</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Christian Religious Knowledge</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Biology</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The subject in question is Christian Religious Knowledge. This is evident from the id of the question which contains 'CRK', an acronym for Christian Religious Knowledge.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE IMPORTANCE OF CHRISTIAN GIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At Shechem, God appeared to Abraham and told him that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he should leave his country</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he should settle there with his descendants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the land would be given to his descendants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he should continue on his journey southwards</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Genesis 12:7, it is recorded that God appeared to Abraham at Shechem and promised that the land would be given to his descendants. This is the basis for the answer.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ABRAHAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Jeremiah, the new covenant is based on</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">restoration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">circumcision</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">providence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the book of Jeremiah, the new covenant is based on righteousness. This is because in the new covenant, God promised to put his law in their minds and write it on their hearts. He will be their God, and they will be his people. This implies a relationship based on righteousness.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : THE NEW COVENANT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joseph's foresight as a leader was exemplified in his</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forgiving his brother for selling him into slavery</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">storing food for seven years of famine</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">service to Potiphar, an officer of Pharaoh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">managing the house of Pharaoh very well</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joseph's foresight as a leader was exemplified in his storing food for seven years of famine. This is evident in the book of Genesis where Joseph interpreted Pharaoh's dream about seven fat cows being eaten by seven lean cows and seven healthy grains being swallowed by seven withered grains. Joseph interpreted this as seven years of plenty followed by seven years of famine and advised Pharaoh to store food during the years of plenty to be used during the years of famine.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JOSEPH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Fear not, stand firm and see the salvation of the LORD, which He will work for you today..\" <br/> Moses made this statement when the Israelites</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were suddenly attacked by the Amalekites</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">became afraid of thunder and lightning at the Mount Sinai</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were trapped between the host of Egypt and the Red Sea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were faced with hunger and death at the Wilderness of Sin</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement was made by Moses when the Israelites were trapped between the host of Egypt and the Red Sea. This was after Pharaoh had let them go, then changed his mind and pursued them. The Israelites were terrified because they were trapped between the Red Sea and the Egyptian army. Moses encouraged them with these words, assuring them of God's salvation.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : EXAMPLES OF ABRAHAM, HEBREW MIDWIVES AND DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the journey of the Israelites in the wilderness, God led them in the day in the form of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fire</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">light</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cloud</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pillar</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the journey of the Israelites in the wilderness, God led them in the day in the form of a cloud. This is recorded in Exodus 13:21, where it is written that the Lord went before them by day in a pillar of cloud to lead them along the way. The cloud provided guidance and also possibly shade in the desert heat.</div>", "topic": "DIVINE PROVIDENCE, GUIDANCE AND PROTECTION :GUIDANCE AND PROTECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Behold, you are old and your sons do not walk in your ways..\"  <br/> The Israelites made this statement to Samuel because his sons</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had immoral dealings with women</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disregarded the advice of Israel's elders</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">took bribes and perverted justice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">considered themselves above the people</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically 1 Samuel 8:3, it is stated that Samuel's sons did not walk in his ways, but turned aside after gain. They took bribes and perverted justice. This is why the Israelites made the statement to Samuel.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JUDGES - DEBORAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David gave Uriah leave to go to his house and wash his feet so as to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">give him time for relaxation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">compensate him for fighting bravely for Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">conceal his adultery with Bathsheba</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">find an excuse to charge him for desertion</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically 2 Samuel 11, David had committed adultery with Bathsheba, Uriah's wife. In an attempt to conceal his sin, David brought Uriah back from the battle and encouraged him to go home and wash his feet, hoping that Uriah would sleep with his wife and believe that the child Bathsheba was carrying was his own.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How did King Solomon demonstrate his wisdom in setting the dispute over the ownership of a baby by the two prostitutes?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He interrogated them for seven days until the truth was discovered</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He interrogated them for only three days and the truth was revealed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He asked them to divide the child into two and the mother was known</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He threatened to give the child to a neutral woman and the mother was known</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, King Solomon demonstrated his wisdom in settling the dispute over the ownership of a baby by two prostitutes by suggesting to divide the child into two. His real intention was not to divide the child but to reveal the true mother who would rather give up her child than see him killed. This story is found in 1 Kings 3:16-28.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : THE WISDOM OF SOLOMON"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul disobeyed God's command through Samuel because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he was misled by the people</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samuel did not come early for the sacrifice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he feared the people and obeyed their voice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people wanted to desert him</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Samuel 15, Saul disobeyed God's command through Samuel because he feared the people and obeyed their voice. He was supposed to completely destroy the Amalekites and their livestock, but he spared King Agag and the best of the livestock. When confronted by Samuel, Saul admitted that he feared the people and listened to them, thus disobeying God's command.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The golden calf which Aaron made for Israel was an evidence of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their fear of the Canaanites</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an attempt to revolt against God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a plot to replace Moses</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lack of faith in God</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The golden calf which Aaron made for Israel was an evidence of their lack of faith in God. When Moses was on Mount Sinai receiving the Ten Commandments, the Israelites grew impatient and asked Aaron to make them a god to worship. This shows their lack of faith in God who had brought them out of Egypt.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to David in the Psalms, God forgives sin so that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the unrighteous may know Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He may be praised</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He may be feared</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sinner may not perish</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to David in the Psalms, God forgives sin so that He may be praised. In Psalm 103:2-3, David says, 'Praise the Lord, my soul, and forget not all his benefits—who forgives all your sins and heals all your diseases.' This suggests that one of the reasons God forgives sin is so that He may be praised for His mercy and love.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFTER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the effects of Solomon's marriage to foreign women was that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he desecrated the Temple of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he lost all wisdom from God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his heart was turned after other gods</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he ceded part of his kingdom to them</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Solomon's marriage to foreign women led him to start worshipping other gods. These women were from nations about which the LORD had told the Israelites, 'You must not intermarry with them, because they will surely turn your hearts after their gods.' Nevertheless, Solomon held fast to them in love. He had seven hundred wives of royal birth and three hundred concubines, and his wives led him astray. As Solomon grew old, his wives turned his heart after other gods, and his heart was not fully devoted to the LORD his God, as the heart of David his father had been. He followed Ashtoreth the goddess of the Sidonians, and Molek the detestable god of the Ammonites. So Solomon did evil in the eyes of the LORD; he did not follow the LORD completely, as David his father had done.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : UNWISE POLICIES OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The failure of Rehoboam to heed to the advice of the old men resulted in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the attack by the Philistines</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the war against Jeroboam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">famine in the land</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">division of the kingdom</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rehoboam's failure to heed the advice of the old men led to the division of the kingdom. When Rehoboam succeeded his father Solomon as king, the people of Israel requested that he lighten the harsh labor and heavy taxes that Solomon had imposed on them. Rehoboam rejected the advice of the older men who had served his father, and instead listened to the advice of the young men he had grown up with. He told the people of Israel that he would be even tougher than his father had been. In response, ten of the twelve tribes of Israel rebelled and chose Jeroboam, an official of Solomon's who had earlier rebelled against the king, to be their leader. The kingdom was divided into the northern kingdom of Israel and the southern kingdom of Judah.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : UNWISE POLICIES OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Consequent upon the murder of Naboth by Ahab, God declared that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sword will never depart from Ahab's house</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He would require the blood of Naboth from Ahab's hand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Dogs would lick Ahab's blood where Naboth's blood was licked</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ahab's descendants would never ascend the throne in Israel</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Kings 21:19, God, through the prophet Elijah, declared to Ahab that 'In the place where dogs licked up Naboth's blood, dogs will lick up your blood—yes, yours!' This was a consequence of Ahab's involvement in the murder of Naboth. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Dogs would lick Ahab's blood where Naboth's blood was licked'.</div>", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : AHAB"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah killed four hundred and fifty prophets of Baal on the Mount Carmel after God has shown His</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Holiness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Omnipresence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Supremacy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Righteousness</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Kings 18:38-40, after God answered Elijah's prayer by sending fire to consume the sacrifice, water, stones, and dust, and also licked up the water in the trench, Elijah ordered the people to seize the prophets of Baal and then he slaughtered them. This event demonstrated God's supremacy over Baal, a false god whose prophets could not call down fire. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Supremacy'.</div>", "topic": "THE SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSION AND THE POWER OF GOD ON MOUNT CARMEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The enormity of the sins before Josiah's reforms was exemplified by their failure to keep the passover since</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the days of Manasseh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the days of all the kings</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the days of the judges of Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were brought out of Egypt</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The enormity of the sins before Josiah's reforms was exemplified by their failure to keep the passover since they were brought out of Egypt. The Passover was a significant event in the history of the Israelites. It was a feast that commemorated their liberation by God from slavery in ancient Egypt and their freedom as a nation under the leadership of Moses. The failure to keep the Passover was a clear indication of the extent of their deviation from God's commandments.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nehemiah, while in exile functioned as the king's</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">servant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">guard</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adviser</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cupbearer</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nehemiah, while in exile, functioned as the king's cupbearer. A cupbearer was an officer of high rank in royal courts, whose duty was to serve the drinks at the royal table. On account of the constant fear of plots and intrigues, a person must be regarded as thoroughly trustworthy to hold this position. He must guard against poison in the king's cup, and was sometimes required to swallow some of the wine before serving it. His confidential relations with the king often gave him a position of great influence. Nehemiah held this position to Artaxerxes, the Persian king.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : CONDITION OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"You have nothing to do with us in building a house to our God...\"  <br/> This statement above made by Zerubbabel and others resulted in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the delay in building the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people rising against their leader</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inciting the Judeans against their leader</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people disobeying King Cyrus' orders</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"You have nothing to do with us in building a house to our God...\" was made by Zerubbabel and others in response to the Samaritans' offer to help build the temple. This refusal led to the Samaritans' opposition and delay in the building of the temple. Therefore, the correct answer is 'the delay in building the Temple'.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Daniel and his friends refused to defile themselves with the king's food, God gave them</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an angel to protect them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vegetables and water only</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">skill in letters and wisdom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the skill to interpret dreams</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Daniel, when Daniel and his friends refused to defile themselves with the king's food, God gave them 'knowledge and skill in all learning and wisdom'. Therefore, the correct answer is 'skill in letters and wisdom'.</div>", "topic": "FAITH, COURAGE AND PROTECTION : EXAMPLES OF DANIEL, SHADRACH, MESHACH AND ABEDNEGO"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's pardon of the people of Nineveh teaches a lesson on the benefits of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">justice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wisdom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">repentance</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The story of God's pardon of the people of Nineveh in the Bible is a lesson on the benefits of repentance. Nineveh was a city that was known for its wickedness. God sent Jonah to warn them of impending destruction unless they repented of their sins. The people of Nineveh heeded Jonah's warning, repented, and God forgave them. This story teaches that repentance can lead to forgiveness from God.</div>", "topic": "GOD'S MESSAGE TO NINEVEH: JONAH AND HIS MESSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea's message to Israel is centred on</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">social justice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the day of judgement</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">divine punishment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">divine love</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea's message to Israel is centred on divine love. Hosea, a prophet in the Bible, was commanded by God to marry a prostitute as a symbolic act to demonstrate God's love for Israel despite their unfaithfulness. Hosea's life and message were a demonstration of God's enduring love for His people, even when they stray from Him.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Behold, this has touched your lips; your guilt is taken away, and you sin forgiven...\"  <br/> The statement above during Isaiah's call shows</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that God will only use sinners to glorify Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's willingness to physically take away sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that God adequately equips His messengers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's ability to identify sinful people</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Behold, this has touched your lips; your guilt is taken away, and you sin forgiven...\" during Isaiah's call shows that God adequately equips His messengers. This is because the act of touching Isaiah's lips with a live coal from the altar symbolizes the purification of Isaiah, making him fit for the divine mission. It is a demonstration of God's provision and preparation for those He calls to serve Him.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The vision of the dry bones by Ezekiel portrays</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hope</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">punishment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">judgement</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">famine</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The vision of the dry bones by Ezekiel portrays hope. In this vision, God showed Ezekiel a valley full of dry bones, which He miraculously brought back to life. This vision was a symbolic message to the Israelites in exile, giving them hope that God could restore them, no matter how desperate their situation seemed.</div>", "topic": "PUNISHMENT AND HOPE : THE CONDITIONS FOR HOPE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Son of man, can these bones live?..\"  <br/> What was God's purpose in asking Ezekiel the question above?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To bring to bear the disobedience of Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To test Ezekiel's obedience</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To show His supremacy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To express faith in man's ability</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's purpose in asking Ezekiel the question was to show His supremacy. In the book of Ezekiel, God asked this question to Ezekiel in a vision where He showed him a valley of dry bones. God was demonstrating His power to bring life to what was dead, thus showing His supremacy.</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The wise men from the East were able to know about the birth of Jesus because they were</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">star-worshippers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">astrologers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">geographers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">explorers</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The wise men from the East were able to know about the birth of Jesus because they were astrologers. The Bible mentions that they saw His star when it rose and have come to worship Him. Astrology is the study of the movements and relative positions of celestial bodies interpreted as having an influence on human affairs and the natural world, which explains how they knew about the birth of Jesus.</div>", "topic": "THE BIRTH AND EARLY LIFE OF JESUS : THE BIRTH AND BOYHOOD OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Who ever does not bear his cross and come after me cannot be my disciple..\"  <br/>  <br/> This statement made by Jesus means that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">one must be prepared to disown his parents</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His followers must carry a cross</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">following Him leads to death on the cross</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">following him demands total surrender and commitment</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Whoever does not bear his cross and come after me cannot be my disciple\" made by Jesus means that following him demands total surrender and commitment. The 'cross' in this context is metaphorical and represents the burdens, sacrifices, and challenges that come with being a disciple of Jesus. It does not literally mean that his followers must carry a physical cross or that following him leads to death on the cross. It also does not mean that one must disown his parents. Therefore, the correct answer is option 4.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A good example of nature miracles performed by Jesus was that of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">raising the dead</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">calming the storm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">healing the leper</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">casting out demons</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A nature miracle is a type of miracle in which the natural world is altered, controlled, or manipulated. This is different from healing miracles (like healing the leper or casting out demons) or resurrection miracles (like raising the dead). The calming of the storm is a nature miracle performed by Jesus as it involved the control of natural elements - wind and waves. Therefore, the correct answer is option 2.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : NATURE MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One important fact that Mary brought out in Jesus' miracle of changing water to wine is that she</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">attended marriage feasts regularly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">must intercede for a miracle to occur</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had a deep insight of her son and His abilities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was a sister of the bride groom</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the miracle of changing water to wine, Mary demonstrated her deep insight of her son and His abilities. She knew that Jesus had the power to perform miracles and she had faith in Him. This is evident when she told the servants, 'Do whatever he tells you' (John 2:5).</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES ABOUT LOVE FOR ONE ANOTHER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable which teaches the need for love for one's neighbours is that of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">good samaritan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sower</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wheat and tares</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mustard seed</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the Good Samaritan teaches the need for love for one's neighbours. In this parable, a man is robbed and left half-dead. A priest and a Levite pass by without helping him, but a Samaritan stops and takes care of him, demonstrating love and compassion for his neighbour (Luke 10:25-37).</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES ABOUT LOVE FOR ONE ANOTHER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who are referred to as the salt of the earth by Jesus in His teaching on the Mount?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The scribes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Those who are condemned for His sake</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His disciples</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Those who are meek</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Sermon on the Mount, Jesus referred to His disciples as the 'salt of the earth'. This metaphor was used to illustrate their value and responsibility in maintaining the faith and spreading the Gospel.</div>", "topic": "SERMON ON THE MOUNT : THE TEACHINGS ON THE MOUNT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the story of the transfiguration of Jesus, Moses and Elijah represented the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Law and the prophets</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Old testament priests</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">glory of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">end of the age</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the story of the transfiguration of Jesus, Moses and Elijah represented the Law and the Prophets. Moses was the lawgiver in the Old Testament, and Elijah was considered one of the greatest prophets. Their appearance during the transfiguration symbolized the fulfillment of the Law and the Prophets in Jesus.</div>", "topic": "THE TRANSFIGURATION : THE EVENTS LEADING TO THE TRANSFIGURATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"..My house shall be called a house of prayer, but you have made it a den of robbers...\"  <br/> Just before making this statement, Jesus</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">went out of the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">locked out of the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">drove out those who sold in the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taught those who sold in the Temple</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Matthew 21:12-13, it is recorded that Jesus drove out all those who sold and bought in the temple, and overturned the tables of the money changers and the seats of those who sold pigeons. He said to them, 'It is written, 'My house shall be called a house of prayer,' but you make it a den of robbers.' Therefore, the correct answer is that Jesus drove out those who sold in the Temple.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Jesus was sent to Herod for trial, he was very glad to see Him because he</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had wanted to punish Jesus for calling him a fox</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had long desired to see Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wanted Jesus to preach to him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">knew Jesus would bless him</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Luke 23:8, it is written that when Herod saw Jesus, he was very glad, for he had long desired to see him, because he had heard about him, and he was hoping to see some sign done by him. Therefore, the correct answer is that Herod had long desired to see Jesus.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : THE TRIALS OF JESUS BEFORE HEROD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Did not our hearts burn within us while he talked to us..\"  <br/> The statement above shows the regret of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the twelve after his arrest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cornelius and his friend</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter's audience at the pentecost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cleopas and one other disciple</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Did not our hearts burn within us while he talked to us..\" was made by Cleopas and another disciple on their way to Emmaus. They made this statement after they had realized that the stranger who had been explaining the scriptures to them was Jesus. They felt a deep sense of regret for not recognizing Him earlier. Therefore, the statement shows the regret of Cleopas and one other disciple.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus as the good shepherd was loved by the father because He</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loved the sheep</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tended the sheep</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">laid down His life for the sheep</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">understood the needs of the sheep</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In John 10:11, Jesus said, \"I am the good shepherd. The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep.\" This statement shows that Jesus was loved by the Father because He was willing to sacrifice His life for the sheep (His followers). Therefore, the correct answer is that Jesus, as the good shepherd, was loved by the Father because He laid down His life for the sheep.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF: THE DOOR THE LAMB AND THE GOOD SHEPHERD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What effect did the death of Aninias and Sapphira have on the Early Church?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">great fear gripped all that ere there</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The disciples became more united</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Apostle Peter was highly respected</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Many more disciples were won to God</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The death of Ananias and Sapphira in the early church, as recorded in Acts 5:1-11, resulted in great fear coming upon all the church and upon all who heard these things. This is because they had lied to the Holy Spirit about the proceeds from the sale of their property, and were struck dead as a result. This event served as a warning to others about the seriousness of lying to God.</div>", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH : PROBLEMS OF COMMUNAL LIVING AND SOLUTIONS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The effect of Stephen's death on the early church was that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it weakened the faith of the apostles</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the believers were arrested</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Chrisitianity was spread to the non-Jews</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it united the church</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Stephen's death, as recorded in Acts 8:1-4, led to a great persecution against the church in Jerusalem, and as a result, the believers were scattered throughout the regions of Judea and Samaria. This scattering of the believers led to the spread of Christianity to non-Jews. Stephen's death, therefore, played a significant role in the expansion of the early church.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : THE MARTYRDOM OF STEPHEN"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The decision at the Council of Jerusalem laid to rest the issue of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">circumcision of all Gentiles for Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abstaining from the pollutions of idols</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">circumcision before one can be saved</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abstaining from unchastity</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Council of Jerusalem, as described in Acts 15, was convened to address the issue of whether Gentiles who converted to Christianity needed to be circumcised to be saved. The council concluded that circumcision was not necessary for salvation, thus laying to rest the issue of 'circumcision before one can be saved'.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COUNCIL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The man who stirred up people against Paul in Ephesus was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Gaius</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Alexander</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Aristarchus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Demetrius</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Acts 19:23-27, Demetrius, a silversmith who made silver shrines of Artemis, stirred up a great commotion against Paul. He did this because he felt that Paul's teachings were bad for business, as they turned people away from the worship of Artemis, thus reducing the demand for his shrines.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : PERSECUTION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Christian concept of justification is that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by one's effort in keeping the Law, man is perfect before God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">through faith in Christ, the sinner is regarded as guiltless before God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">through his own knowledge, man can do what is pleasing to God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by his natural wisdom, a sinner could be reconciled to God</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Justification in Christian theology is the process by which a person is made or declared 'just', that is, made or declared to be in right standing before God. This is achieved not by one's effort or knowledge but through faith in Jesus Christ. Therefore, the correct answer is 'through faith in Christ, the sinner is regarded as guiltless before God'.</div>", "topic": "JUSTIFICATION BY FAITH : MEANING AND BASIC CONDITIONS FOR JUSTIFICATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Epistle of Paul to the Corinthians, when God reconciled believers to Him through Christ, He gave them the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ministry of reconciliation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">world to protect</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ability to sin no more</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">grace to be his friends</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Epistle of Paul to the Corinthians, specifically in 2 Corinthians 5:18, it is stated that God reconciled us to himself through Christ and gave us the ministry of reconciliation. Therefore, the correct answer is 'ministry of reconciliation'.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : HOW CHRISTIANS ARE JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What did Paul advise the Philippians to manifest as a virtue of humility?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">regarding themselves as superior to others</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taking the lowest seat in a gathering</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">counting others as better than themselves</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">counting others equal to them</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Philippians 2:3, Paul advises the Philippians to do nothing out of selfish ambition or vain conceit. Rather, in humility, they should value others above themselves. This means they should count others as better than themselves.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul, Christian should forgive one another so that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their prayers may be heard by God in Heaven</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God may forgive them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they may not perish in sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Satan may not gain advantage over them</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 2 Corinthians 2:10-11, Paul advises Christians to forgive one another so that Satan might not outwit them, for they are not unaware of his schemes. This means that forgiveness is necessary to prevent Satan from gaining an advantage over them.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul, spiritual gifts are for the benefit of the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">infrastructure of the church</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">corporate life of the Body of Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">individual members of the congregation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">edification of the Lord</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Apostle Paul in the New Testament of the Bible, spiritual gifts are given for the benefit of the corporate life of the Body of Christ. This means that these gifts are not for individual gain or for the infrastructure of the church, but for the collective good of all believers, to build up the church as a whole.</div>", "topic": "SPIRITUAL GIFTS : THE BENEFITS OF SPIRITUAL GIFTS TO THE INDIVIDUAL AND THE CHURCH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul's prayer for the Philippians was that God who inspired them to give him gifts would surely</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">accept their offering</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enrich them on earth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive all the glory</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">supply all their needs</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Philippians 4:19, Paul's prayer for the Philippians was that God who inspired them to give him gifts would surely supply all their needs. This is a promise that God will provide for the needs of those who are generous in their giving.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE IMPORTANCE OF CHRISTIAN GIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul advised Christians in Thessalonica to keep away from any brother who is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">living in sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not proclaiming the gospel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">very stingy in giving</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">living in idleness</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 2 Thessalonians 3:6, Paul advises the Thessalonians to keep away from any brother who is living in idleness, not in accordance with the tradition that they received from him. This means that the correct answer is 'living in idleness'.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE REQUIREMENTS OF GOOD CITIZENSHIP."}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul, the second coming of Christ will take place</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suddenly and unexpectedly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">when sin shall be no more</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">after the reign of the saints</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in our life time</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Thessalonians 5:2, Paul states that the day of the Lord will come like a thief in the night, which means it will happen suddenly and unexpectedly. Therefore, the correct answer is 'suddenly and unexpectedly'.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : THE SIGNS OF THE COMING OF CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to James, effective prayer is that which is offered</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">silently</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">with emotion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loudly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in faith</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the book of James in the Bible, effective prayer is that which is offered in faith. This is based on James 5:15 which says 'And the prayer of faith will save the one who is sick, and the Lord will raise him up.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'in faith'.</div>", "topic": "EFFECTIVE PRAYER : THE REQUIREMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRAYER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2014>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Peter, the fact that judgement would begin with the household of God means that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all must face God's judgement day</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">avoidance of persecution would lead nowhere</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Christians should court persecution to win glory</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the persecution of Christians would be less severe</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Peter in the Bible, the fact that judgement would begin with the household of God means that all must face God's judgement day. This is based on 1 Peter 4:17 which says 'For it is time for judgment to begin at the household of God; and if it begins with us, what will be the outcome for those who do not obey the gospel of God?' Therefore, the correct answer is 'all must face God's judgement day'.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : THE BENEFITS OF BEING JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}];
